","Foxley, Bray, Berkshire, England":"Bray, Berkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Foxley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places so called, such as Foxley in Blakesley (Northamptonshire), Foxley Hall in Lymm (Cheshire), Foxley (Norfolk), Foxley in Coulsdon (Surrey), Foxley in Yazor (Herefordshire), Foxley (Wiltshire), and Foxley Corner in Urchfont (also Wiltshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>fox</i> ‘fox’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘clearing, open woodland’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isabell","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":19,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabell de Foxley was born in 1296, in Bray, Berkshire, England, her father, John de Foxley, was 26 and her mother, Lady Constancia de la Hoese, Heiress-Apparent of the de Bramshill family, was 19. She married John Fowler II in 1315, in Berkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1324, in Shrivenham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 28, and was buried in Shrivenham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1296–1324":"1296–1324","1291–1360":"1291–1360","1295–1361":"1295–1361","1320–1361":"1320–1361","1322–1420":"1322–1420","1350–1412":"1350–1412","1270–1325"